Dialogue: 0,0:00:01.02,0:00:04.89,Default,,0,0,0,,When we think of Acts 1:8, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:04.89,0:00:07.72,Default,,0,0,0,,we think of this challenging assignment \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:07.72,0:00:10.09,Default,,0,0,0,,that the apostles were given, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:10.09,0:00:13.73,Default,,0,0,0,,and we can only just imagine \Nthem thinking about \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:13.73,0:00:17.57,Default,,0,0,0,,the other promise of “power” \Nand “holy spirit” being with them. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:17.57,0:00:22.01,Default,,0,0,0,,They certainly would need that to go \N“to the most distant part of the earth.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:22.01,0:00:24.54,Default,,0,0,0,,When we think back \Nto the first century, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:24.54,0:00:28.45,Default,,0,0,0,,we think of ones such as \Nthe apostle Paul, Barnabas, Timothy, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:28.45,0:00:31.15,Default,,0,0,0,,and many others \Nwho literally tried to go \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:31.15,0:00:35.09,Default,,0,0,0,,as far as they could \Nto reach various territories.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:35.09,0:00:37.45,Default,,0,0,0,,If we take our Bibles \Nand turn to the book \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:37.45,0:00:42.46,Default,,0,0,0,,of Romans 15:23, 24, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:42.46,0:00:45.16,Default,,0,0,0,,we see summarized here \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:45.16,0:00:48.47,Default,,0,0,0,,the apostle Paul’s viewpoint \Nwith regard to this. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:48.47,0:00:51.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Romans 15:23: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:51.07,0:00:55.14,Default,,0,0,0,,“But now I no longer have \Nuntouched territory in these regions, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:55.14,0:00:57.47,Default,,0,0,0,,and for many years \NI have longed to come to you.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:57.47,0:00:59.48,Default,,0,0,0,,And that’s the brothers in Rome. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:59.48,0:01:03.58,Default,,0,0,0,,“Therefore, when I journey to Spain, \NI hope that I will see you.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:03.58,0:01:08.52,Default,,0,0,0,,So Paul was very concerned \Nabout going to untouched territories.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:08.52,0:01:10.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, in recent times, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:10.52,0:01:13.19,Default,,0,0,0,,we can say the same \Nis true of Jehovah’s people, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:13.19,0:01:16.86,Default,,0,0,0,,whether it be the Gilead missionaries \Nwho have been sent out \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:16.86,0:01:18.86,Default,,0,0,0,,or other missionaries even prior \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:18.86,0:01:21.83,Default,,0,0,0,,to the time of Gilead \Nbeing established. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:21.83,0:01:25.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Or we think of the brothers \Nwho have moved to other countries \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:25.27,0:01:27.27,Default,,0,0,0,,to serve where the need is greater \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:27.27,0:01:31.11,Default,,0,0,0,,or perhaps those who \Nhave gone out to unassigned territories \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:31.11,0:01:34.38,Default,,0,0,0,,or helped in areas \Nwhere very few people \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:34.38,0:01:36.88,Default,,0,0,0,,get the opportunity \Nto hear the message. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:36.88,0:01:38.88,Default,,0,0,0,,When we hear \Nthose experiences, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:38.88,0:01:42.29,Default,,0,0,0,,we certainly are encouraged \Nby them, aren’t we?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:42.29,0:01:44.52,Default,,0,0,0,,But perhaps we \Ncould think this morning \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:44.52,0:01:48.96,Default,,0,0,0,,about just one of the aspects \Nof the history in the past. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:48.96,0:01:52.96,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s something referred to \Nin the March 2016 Watchtower, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:52.96,0:01:54.96,Default,,0,0,0,,in the “Questions From Readers.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:54.96,0:01:56.97,Default,,0,0,0,,You remember this was discussing \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:56.97,0:02:01.10,Default,,0,0,0,,the valley of dry bones \Nin Ezekiel 37. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:01.10,0:02:04.24,Default,,0,0,0,,It spoke about \Nthe gradual restoration \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:04.24,0:02:06.54,Default,,0,0,0,,of true worship, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:06.54,0:02:09.48,Default,,0,0,0,,and it made the comment \Nthere that in the Scriptures, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:09.48,0:02:12.22,Default,,0,0,0,,it speaks of a “rattling” noise. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:12.22,0:02:14.22,Default,,0,0,0,,And The Watchtower \Nmade this comment, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:14.22,0:02:17.65,Default,,0,0,0,,it said that even \Nprior to the time of the end, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:17.65,0:02:19.79,Default,,0,0,0,,there were some \Nfaithful individuals \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:19.79,0:02:21.96,Default,,0,0,0,,who stood up \Nin behalf of true worship. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:21.96,0:02:25.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Then it said: \N“Some of them endeavored to produce Bibles \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:25.60,0:02:28.53,Default,,0,0,0,,in the languages of the common people.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:28.53,0:02:32.84,Default,,0,0,0,,So let’s just think \Nfor a few moments about some of those\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:32.84,0:02:34.94,Default,,0,0,0,,—perhaps less than 100 years \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:34.94,0:02:39.31,Default,,0,0,0,,before the time that Brother Russell \Nstarted The Watchtower—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:39.31,0:02:42.78,Default,,0,0,0,,and how many \Nof those were motivated \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:42.78,0:02:45.72,Default,,0,0,0,,to go to distant parts \Nof the earth \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:45.72,0:02:49.12,Default,,0,0,0,,to translate the Bible \Nand help others there.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:49.12,0:02:52.69,Default,,0,0,0,,For example, \Nin the year 1793, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:52.69,0:02:55.29,Default,,0,0,0,,a man by the name \Nof William Carey \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:55.29,0:02:57.96,Default,,0,0,0,,was a British shoemaker. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:57.96,0:03:02.13,Default,,0,0,0,,And this shoemaker \Nwas very impressed with the words \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:02.13,0:03:04.73,Default,,0,0,0,,recorded at Matthew 28:19, 20. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:04.73,0:03:09.47,Default,,0,0,0,,He felt strongly that all Christians \Nshould follow that command. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:09.47,0:03:12.14,Default,,0,0,0,,So his goal was to go to India. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:12.14,0:03:16.55,Default,,0,0,0,,And he arrived in India \Nand faced all sorts of problems\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:16.55,0:03:19.82,Default,,0,0,0,,—eventually his wife died, \Nhis son died as well, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:19.82,0:03:22.82,Default,,0,0,0,,he had to take \Na job planting indigo. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:22.82,0:03:26.96,Default,,0,0,0,,But this man, within 21 years, \Nwith the help of some others, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:26.96,0:03:30.43,Default,,0,0,0,,was able to translate the Bible, \Nwell, parts of it, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:30.43,0:03:33.90,Default,,0,0,0,,in 36 languages.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:33.90,0:03:37.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Then in 1797, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:37.03,0:03:39.20,Default,,0,0,0,,another man, \NHenry Nott, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:39.20,0:03:43.41,Default,,0,0,0,,from England \Nwas a bricklayer. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:43.41,0:03:47.58,Default,,0,0,0,,And he and quite a number \Nof others arrived in Tahiti. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:47.58,0:03:50.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, four of those on that ship \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:50.45,0:03:53.05,Default,,0,0,0,,were noted to be pastors, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:53.05,0:03:56.42,Default,,0,0,0,,but they had \Nno formal training whatsoever. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:56.42,0:04:00.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Henry Nott hadn’t had \Na very good education. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:00.29,0:04:04.13,Default,,0,0,0,,He was a bricklayer; \Nhe just had the basic education. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:04.13,0:04:06.70,Default,,0,0,0,,But this very faithful man \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:06.70,0:04:09.50,Default,,0,0,0,,decided to learn Hebrew and Greek \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:09.50,0:04:12.14,Default,,0,0,0,,and translate the Bible into Tahitian. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:12.14,0:04:14.54,Default,,0,0,0,,And he learned Tahitian very quickly, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:14.54,0:04:18.68,Default,,0,0,0,,and in 1835, \Nafter 30 years of translating, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:18.68,0:04:21.21,Default,,0,0,0,,it says that he put down his quill \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:21.21,0:04:25.62,Default,,0,0,0,,and the Tahitian Bible, which, \Nincidentally, uses Jehovah’s name \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:25.62,0:04:29.35,Default,,0,0,0,,in both the Hebrew \Nand the Greek sections of the Bible.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:29.35,0:04:33.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Then 1807, \NRobert Morrison\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:33.12,0:04:37.59,Default,,0,0,0,,—a man who was determined \Nto translate the Bible into Chinese. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:37.59,0:04:39.73,Default,,0,0,0,,He arrived in China to find out \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:39.73,0:04:42.27,Default,,0,0,0,,that if anyone \Ntaught a foreigner Chinese, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:42.27,0:04:44.33,Default,,0,0,0,,there was a death penalty. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:44.33,0:04:46.84,Default,,0,0,0,,So he remained indoors \Nfor a couple of years \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:46.84,0:04:49.57,Default,,0,0,0,,while he learned \Nthe Chinese language. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:49.57,0:04:52.98,Default,,0,0,0,,And then when he \Nstarted to translate the Bible, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:52.98,0:04:56.81,Default,,0,0,0,,he found out the emperor \Nhad stated there would be a death penalty \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:56.81,0:05:01.32,Default,,0,0,0,,for anyone who printed \NChristian literature in that country. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:01.32,0:05:03.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, in 1819, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:03.85,0:05:08.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Morrison completed \Nhis version there of the Bible.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:08.52,0:05:12.43,Default,,0,0,0,,In 1812, \NJudson, an American, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:12.43,0:05:15.60,Default,,0,0,0,,along with his wife, \Nleft America \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:15.60,0:05:18.47,Default,,0,0,0,,just after two weeks \Nof marriage and, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:18.47,0:05:21.47,Default,,0,0,0,,in 1813, \Narrived in Burma, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:21.47,0:05:23.77,Default,,0,0,0,,which is now known \Nas Myanmar. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:23.77,0:05:26.71,Default,,0,0,0,,And his determination \Nwas to translate \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:26.71,0:05:29.81,Default,,0,0,0,,the Bible into the local language, \Nwhich was very hard there. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:29.81,0:05:31.81,Default,,0,0,0,,There was no dictionary; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:31.81,0:05:34.62,Default,,0,0,0,,there was no one \Nthat could actually teach him, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:34.62,0:05:38.12,Default,,0,0,0,,and yet he set \Nto learning the language. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:38.12,0:05:41.42,Default,,0,0,0,,He had a period of time \Nwhere he was in prison \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:41.42,0:05:45.73,Default,,0,0,0,,with three pairs of iron fetters \Nattached to his body. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:45.73,0:05:48.46,Default,,0,0,0,,And he was very concerned \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:48.46,0:05:50.97,Default,,0,0,0,,about his Bible manuscript \Nthat he’d been translating, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:50.97,0:05:53.60,Default,,0,0,0,,which was hidden \Nin the earth under his home. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:53.60,0:05:56.77,Default,,0,0,0,,His wife eventually brought it \Nto him in prison. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:56.77,0:05:58.84,Default,,0,0,0,,It was hidden in a pillow. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:58.84,0:06:02.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, this man, \Nby 1835, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:02.28,0:06:06.45,Default,,0,0,0,,had the Bible translated \Ninto the local language there.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:06.45,0:06:09.49,Default,,0,0,0,,But not all of these \Nwere white missionaries \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:09.49,0:06:12.49,Default,,0,0,0,,from either America or England. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:12.49,0:06:16.16,Default,,0,0,0,,When the message \Nreached the Pacific, for example, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:16.16,0:06:19.23,Default,,0,0,0,,many local persons\N—Polynesians—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:19.23,0:06:23.30,Default,,0,0,0,,were very determined to go \Nto other islands within the Pacific \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:23.30,0:06:25.33,Default,,0,0,0,,to spread the message. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:25.33,0:06:28.17,Default,,0,0,0,,An example of this is in 1823. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:28.17,0:06:31.34,Default,,0,0,0,,A man, \Na Polynesian by the name of Papeiha, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:31.34,0:06:35.95,Default,,0,0,0,,was determined to get \Nthe message in Rarotonga, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:35.95,0:06:37.95,Default,,0,0,0,,in the Cook Islands. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:37.95,0:06:40.48,Default,,0,0,0,,So the mission ship arrived there; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:40.48,0:06:44.22,Default,,0,0,0,,the two missionary couples \Nfrom overseas, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:44.22,0:06:47.16,Default,,0,0,0,,white missionaries, \Nwere put ashore. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:47.16,0:06:50.03,Default,,0,0,0,,There was a misunderstanding \Nwith a drunken king, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:50.03,0:06:52.53,Default,,0,0,0,,which resulted in them \Nbeing beaten up, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:52.53,0:06:54.60,Default,,0,0,0,,all their possessions \Nbeing stolen, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:54.60,0:06:57.60,Default,,0,0,0,,and them fleeing back \Nto the ship. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:57.60,0:07:01.00,Default,,0,0,0,,But Papeiha was determined \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:01.00,0:07:04.57,Default,,0,0,0,,to take the Gospel message \Nto those islanders. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:04.57,0:07:08.21,Default,,0,0,0,,So it’s reported that he said \Nthat he would swim ashore \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:08.21,0:07:10.21,Default,,0,0,0,,and that he called out: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:10.21,0:07:12.22,Default,,0,0,0,,“Ko Jehova toku tiaki! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:12.22,0:07:14.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Tei roto au i tona rima!” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:14.22,0:07:16.22,Default,,0,0,0,,which translated means \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:16.22,0:07:18.22,Default,,0,0,0,,“Jehovah is my shepherd! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:18.22,0:07:20.22,Default,,0,0,0,,I am in His hand!” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:20.22,0:07:22.93,Default,,0,0,0,,And holding a book \Nwith some translations \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:22.93,0:07:24.93,Default,,0,0,0,,of the Bible in Tahitian, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:24.93,0:07:27.13,Default,,0,0,0,,he jumped overboard, \Nswam ashore, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:27.13,0:07:29.97,Default,,0,0,0,,and started preaching \Nto the local people.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:29.97,0:07:33.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, you can’t help \Nbut admire that enthusiasm. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:33.87,0:07:36.51,Default,,0,0,0,,The conditions \Nthat these missionaries met \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:36.51,0:07:40.34,Default,,0,0,0,,were very, very difficult, \Nvery primitive conditions. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:40.34,0:07:43.51,Default,,0,0,0,,In one country, \Nthe missionaries lived in villages \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:43.51,0:07:47.68,Default,,0,0,0,,where people \Nstill practiced cannibalism and, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:47.68,0:07:50.29,Default,,0,0,0,,in many cases, \Nwhen the chief died, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:50.29,0:07:54.62,Default,,0,0,0,,all his wives were executed \Nat that point and buried with him. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:54.62,0:07:57.29,Default,,0,0,0,,So in the midst \Nof these conditions, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:57.29,0:08:01.23,Default,,0,0,0,,these men translated \Nthe Bible and, in many cases, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:01.23,0:08:03.90,Default,,0,0,0,,used Jehovah’s name \Nnot only in the Bible \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:03.90,0:08:06.57,Default,,0,0,0,,but in their personal writings.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:06.57,0:08:08.91,Default,,0,0,0,,What kept them going? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:08.91,0:08:12.58,Default,,0,0,0,,What helped them to go \Nto these distant parts of the earth? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:12.58,0:08:16.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, a book on the history \Nof the missionary work in the Pacific \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:16.11,0:08:18.11,Default,,0,0,0,,makes this interesting comment. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:18.11,0:08:21.78,Default,,0,0,0,,It says: \N“Strong faith in Jehovah \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:21.78,0:08:25.69,Default,,0,0,0,,often overcame fear and despair.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:25.69,0:08:27.69,Default,,0,0,0,,What an interesting thought. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:27.69,0:08:30.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, the obvious question is, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:30.23,0:08:32.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Were these ones anointed? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:32.73,0:08:34.80,Default,,0,0,0,,The answer obviously is, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:34.80,0:08:36.80,Default,,0,0,0,,We don’t know. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:36.80,0:08:40.04,Default,,0,0,0,,But we do know \Nthat Jesus said in Matthew 13 \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:40.04,0:08:43.17,Default,,0,0,0,,there would be \Nwheatlike “sons of the Kingdom” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:43.17,0:08:45.17,Default,,0,0,0,,right down through history. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:45.17,0:08:47.48,Default,,0,0,0,,And if some of them \Nwere involved with this type of work, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:47.48,0:08:49.65,Default,,0,0,0,,I’m sure we wouldn’t be surprised. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:49.65,0:08:52.62,Default,,0,0,0,,And in the future, \Nwe will no doubt find out \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:52.62,0:08:55.18,Default,,0,0,0,,if they were involved \Nwith that work or not.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:55.18,0:08:57.69,Default,,0,0,0,,But what about us today? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:57.69,0:09:00.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, does it mean we \Nhave to all leave our Bethel homes now \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:00.86,0:09:03.23,Default,,0,0,0,,and go to the most distant parts \Nof the earth? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:03.23,0:09:05.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, remember, \Nin Acts 1:8, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:05.23,0:09:08.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Jesus was speaking to people \Nthere in Jerusalem, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:08.50,0:09:10.83,Default,,0,0,0,,and you may already be living \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:10.83,0:09:13.17,Default,,0,0,0,,in one of the most distant parts \Nof the earth \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:13.17,0:09:16.01,Default,,0,0,0,,when you view it \Nfrom Jerusalem’s viewpoint. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:16.01,0:09:19.74,Default,,0,0,0,,But the main thing is, \Nwherever we are\N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:19.74,0:09:22.35,Default,,0,0,0,,—if we can reach out \Nand go somewhere else \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:22.35,0:09:25.28,Default,,0,0,0,,or whether we can preach \Nwithin our own territory—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:25.28,0:09:28.58,Default,,0,0,0,,if we follow the example \Nof these faithful ones, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:28.58,0:09:31.82,Default,,0,0,0,,we’ll be sure to try \Nand reach out to persons \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:31.82,0:09:34.62,Default,,0,0,0,,who have not had \Nthe opportunity to hear the truth, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:34.62,0:09:35.61,Default,,0,0,0,,whether near or far.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:02.49,0:00:05.56,Default2,,0,0,0,,わたしたちは 使徒 1章8節を読む時—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:05.56,0:00:10.66,Default2,,0,0,0,,使徒たちに与えられた\N割り当ての大きさについて考えます\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:10.66,0:00:12.70,Default2,,0,0,0,,使徒たちは“力”や “聖霊” が—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:12.70,0:00:16.67,Default2,,0,0,0,,共にいるという約束について\N考えたかもしれません\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:16.67,0:00:22.87,Default2,,0,0,0,,それなしでは “地の最も遠い所” にまで\N行くことはできないからです\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:22.87,0:00:28.04,Default2,,0,0,0,,1世紀当時のパウロ バルナバ テモテ\Nその他多くの人々は—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:28.04,0:00:35.72,Default2,,0,0,0,,文字通り 可能な限り遠くの区域に\N達するよう懸命に働きました\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:35.72,0:00:36.85,Default2,,0,0,0,,聖書を開いて—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:36.85,0:00:42.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,ローマ 15章23, 24節を\Nご覧ください\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:43.49,0:00:48.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,遠くの区域に達することに関する\Nパウロの見方がこうあります\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:49.07,0:00:50.23,Default2,,0,0,0,,“しかし今はもう—”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.23,0:00:53.37,Default2,,0,0,0,,“この地方に[手のつけられていない]区域は\N ありませんし—”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:53.37,0:00:56.01,Default2,,0,0,0,,“スペインに赴く際には\N あなた方のもとに行きたいと—”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:56.01,0:00:58.17,Default2,,0,0,0,,“幾年も切望してきましたので—”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:58.17,0:01:00.34,Default2,,0,0,0,,“そこへの旅の途中でともかく—”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:00.34,0:01:04.15,Default2,,0,0,0,,“あなた方に一目会い［たい］”\Nとあります\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:04.15,0:01:05.35,Default2,,0,0,0,,ですから パウロは—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:05.35,0:01:09.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,手のつけられていない区域に\N強い関心がありました\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:10.72,0:01:14.76,Default2,,0,0,0,,近年のエホバの民も\N同様の関心を抱いてきました\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:14.76,0:01:17.13,Default2,,0,0,0,,宣教者がギレアデ学校から—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:17.13,0:01:21.46,Default2,,0,0,0,,また その学校が設立される以前からも\N送り出されてきましたし—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:21.46,0:01:28.47,Default2,,0,0,0,,多くの兄弟たちが 必要の大きな他の国に\N住まいを移して奉仕しています\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:28.47,0:01:31.31,Default2,,0,0,0,,どの会衆にも\N割り当てられていない区域や—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:31.31,0:01:34.11,Default2,,0,0,0,,ほとんどの人が証言を受けていない\N地域に出向いて—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:34.11,0:01:37.55,Default2,,0,0,0,,奉仕する兄弟たちもいます\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:37.55,0:01:39.42,Default2,,0,0,0,,このような兄弟たちの働きは—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:39.42,0:01:43.59,Default2,,0,0,0,,確かに わたしたちの大きな励みです\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:43.59,0:01:48.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,しかし今日は 過去の歴史の一つの面に\N目を向けてみましょう\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:49.89,0:01:54.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,「ものみの塔」2016年3月号の\N「読者からの質問」には—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:55.20,0:01:57.53,Default2,,0,0,0,,乾いた骨の谷について述べた—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:57.53,0:02:01.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,エゼキエル37章が\N取り上げられています \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:02.54,0:02:06.68,Default2,,0,0,0,,その記事は 真の崇拝が\N徐々に回復されることと—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:06.68,0:02:11.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,聖句にある “かたかたという” 音に\N関する注解があります\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:14.58,0:02:18.05,Default2,,0,0,0,,その記事は\N終わりの時の始まる前でさえ—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:18.05,0:02:21.83,Default2,,0,0,0,,忠実な人々が\N真の崇拝のために立ち上がり—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:21.83,0:02:27.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,“一般の人々の言語に聖書を翻訳しようと\N した人たちもいました” と述べています\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:30.27,0:02:34.24,Default2,,0,0,0,,これから そのような人たちについて\N考えてみましょう\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:34.24,0:02:37.04,Default2,,0,0,0,,ラッセル兄弟が\N「ものみの塔」誌の発行を始める—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:37.04,0:02:39.81,Default2,,0,0,0,,100年ほど前になります\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:39.81,0:02:44.18,Default2,,0,0,0,,彼らの多くが どれほど強く促されて\N遠い所にまで赴き—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:44.18,0:02:49.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,聖書を翻訳し 現地の人々を助けたかを\N考えてみましょう\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:50.55,0:02:53.99,Default2,,0,0,0,,例えば 1793年のことです\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:53.99,0:02:56.59,Default2,,0,0,0,,ウィリアム・ケアリー\Nという名の男性は—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:56.59,0:02:59.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,英国の 靴職人でしたが—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:59.00,0:03:03.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,この人はマタイ 28章19, 20節\Nの言葉にとても感動し—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:04.10,0:03:09.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,すべてのクリスチャンはこの命令に\N従うべきだと強く感じました\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:10.11,0:03:12.74,Default2,,0,0,0,,そして インドに行くことにします\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:12.74,0:03:16.88,Default2,,0,0,0,,到着してから\Nあらゆる問題に直面しました\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:16.88,0:03:19.48,Default2,,0,0,0,,妻を そして息子を失い—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:19.48,0:03:23.79,Default2,,0,0,0,,インド藍栽培の職に\N就かなければなりませんでした\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:23.79,0:03:27.46,Default2,,0,0,0,,しかし 彼とその仲間たちは\N21年ほどで—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:27.46,0:03:34.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,聖書全巻あるいはその一部を\N36の言語に翻訳しました\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:35.40,0:03:39.10,Default2,,0,0,0,,別の例として 1797年—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:39.10,0:03:44.14,Default2,,0,0,0,,英国出身で れんが職人の\Nヘンリー・ノットがいます\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:44.14,0:03:49.45,Default2,,0,0,0,,彼は 他の多くの人と共に\Nタヒチに到着しました\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:49.45,0:03:51.95,Default2,,0,0,0,,彼らのうち4人は牧師でしたが—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:51.95,0:03:55.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,正規の訓練は\N何も受けていませんでした\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:57.85,0:04:00.09,Default2,,0,0,0,,ヘンリー・ノットは\Nれんが職人で—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:00.09,0:04:04.46,Default2,,0,0,0,,基礎的な教育しか受けていませんでした\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:04.46,0:04:08.83,Default2,,0,0,0,,しかし 忠実なこの人は\Nヘブライ語とギリシャ語を学び—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:08.83,0:04:12.70,Default2,,0,0,0,,聖書をタヒチ語に\N翻訳することにしました\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:12.70,0:04:15.34,Default2,,0,0,0,,彼は タヒチ語をすぐに覚え—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:15.34,0:04:18.57,Default2,,0,0,0,,30年後の1835年—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:18.57,0:04:22.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,ついにタヒチ語への\N聖書翻訳を終えました\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:23.11,0:04:25.68,Default2,,0,0,0,,その聖書のヘブライ語とギリシャ語\N双方に—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:25.68,0:04:28.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,エホバのみ名が記されています\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:31.15,0:04:33.96,Default2,,0,0,0,,1807年 ロバート・モリソンは—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:33.96,0:04:37.86,Default2,,0,0,0,,聖書を中国語に翻訳する決意をしました\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:37.86,0:04:40.43,Default2,,0,0,0,,中国に到着して分かったことは—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:40.43,0:04:45.60,Default2,,0,0,0,,外国人に中国語を教える者は\N死刑に処されることです\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:45.60,0:04:51.44,Default2,,0,0,0,,彼は 数年間 家にこもり\Nその間 中国語を学びます\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:51.44,0:04:55.88,Default2,,0,0,0,,そして 聖書の翻訳に取りかかったものの\N出された皇帝の布告は—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:55.88,0:05:01.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,中国でキリスト教の文書を印刷する者は\N死刑に処す というものでした\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:02.65,0:05:08.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,それでも1819年 モリソンは\N中国語訳を完成させました\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:09.13,0:05:12.96,Default2,,0,0,0,,1812年 ジャドソンと彼の妻は—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:12.96,0:05:17.07,Default2,,0,0,0,,結婚して わずか2週間後に\N米国を出発し—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:17.07,0:05:23.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,1813年に ビルマ\N現在のミャンマーに到着しました\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:24.54,0:05:27.88,Default2,,0,0,0,,彼は聖書を現地語に翻訳する決意で\Nいましたが—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:27.88,0:05:29.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,困難な仕事でした\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:30.45,0:05:34.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,辞書はなく\N教えてくれる人は一人もいませんでした\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:35.12,0:05:39.16,Default2,,0,0,0,,それでも 言語を学ぶことを\Nあきらめませんでした\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:39.16,0:05:45.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,3組の足かせをかけられ\N投獄された時期もありました\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:46.33,0:05:48.93,Default2,,0,0,0,,そんな時にも彼が心配したのは—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:48.93,0:05:53.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,家の床下に隠した\N聖書の翻訳原稿のことでした\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:54.24,0:05:57.14,Default2,,0,0,0,,後に ジャドソン夫人は\Nそれを枕に隠して—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:57.14,0:05:59.34,Default2,,0,0,0,,獄中の夫に届けました\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:59.34,0:06:06.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,そして 1835年 ついに彼は\N現地語の聖書を完成させました\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:07.75,0:06:13.82,Default2,,0,0,0,,しかし 米国や英国からの\N白人の宣教師ばかりではありません\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:13.82,0:06:17.66,Default2,,0,0,0,,例えば\N聖書の音信が南太平洋に届くと—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:17.66,0:06:20.23,Default2,,0,0,0,,大勢の 現地のポリネシア人が—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:20.23,0:06:25.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,他の島々に音信を伝える強い決意を\N抱くようになりました\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:26.20,0:06:28.50,Default2,,0,0,0,,例えば 1823年— \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:28.50,0:06:31.24,Default2,,0,0,0,,ポリネシア人のパペイーハは—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:31.24,0:06:37.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,クック諸島のラロトンガ島に音信を\N伝えたいとの強い願いを抱きました\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:39.52,0:06:42.22,Default2,,0,0,0,,宣教師の船が 島に到着し—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:42.22,0:06:46.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,白人宣教師である\N二組の夫婦が上陸します\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:48.72,0:06:51.93,Default2,,0,0,0,,ところが 泥酔した王との間に\N誤解が生じ—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:51.93,0:06:55.23,Default2,,0,0,0,,ひどく打ちたたかれ\N持ち物はすべて盗まれ—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:55.23,0:06:58.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,船に逃げ帰る結果になりました\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:59.30,0:07:01.27,Default2,,0,0,0,,しかし パペイーハは 是非とも—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:01.27,0:07:05.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,福音をその島民に伝えたい\Nと思っていました\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:06.24,0:07:10.51,Default2,,0,0,0,,記録によれば\N彼は岸に向かって泳ぐと言い—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:10.51,0:07:12.75,Default2,,0,0,0,,“コー ジェホーバ トーク ティアーキ！”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:12.75,0:07:14.65,Default2,,0,0,0,,“テイ ロト アウ イ トーナ リーマ！”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:14.65,0:07:16.72,Default2,,0,0,0,,と叫びました\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:16.72,0:07:19.62,Default2,,0,0,0,,これは “エホバは我が牧者—”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:19.62,0:07:22.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,“我はみ手のうちにあり！”\Nという意味です\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:23.49,0:07:25.60,Default2,,0,0,0,,タヒチ語の聖句の載った本を持ち—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:25.60,0:07:27.40,Default2,,0,0,0,,海に飛び込んで 岸に向かい—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:27.40,0:07:29.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,そして 伝道し始めました\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:31.47,0:07:34.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,称賛に値する熱心さです\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:36.91,0:07:40.54,Default2,,0,0,0,,これらの宣教師が直面した状況は\N困難を極め—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:40.54,0:07:43.55,Default2,,0,0,0,,大変野蛮なものもありました\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:43.55,0:07:48.25,Default2,,0,0,0,,ある国の宣教師が住んでいた村では\N人食いの習慣があり—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:48.25,0:07:51.85,Default2,,0,0,0,,村長が死ぬと 多くの場合\Nその妻たちも殺され—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:51.85,0:07:54.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,村長と共に埋葬されます\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:56.66,0:07:59.40,Default2,,0,0,0,,そのような中で 彼らは聖書を翻訳し—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:59.40,0:08:02.70,Default2,,0,0,0,,多くの場合 エホバのみ名を\N聖書だけでなく—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:02.70,0:08:05.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,個人の著作にも記しました\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:07.77,0:08:09.37,Default2,,0,0,0,,彼らを駆り立て—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:09.37,0:08:13.54,Default2,,0,0,0,,遠くの地に向かわせたのは\N何だったのでしょうか？\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:13.54,0:08:19.92,Default2,,0,0,0,,南太平洋の宣教活動に関する歴史本には\N次のような言葉があります\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:19.92,0:08:25.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,“エホバに対する強い信仰は\N 恐れと絶望に打ち勝つ”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:26.46,0:08:29.46,Default2,,0,0,0,,実に示唆に富んだ言葉です\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:29.46,0:08:30.53,Default2,,0,0,0,,ところで—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:30.53,0:08:33.90,Default2,,0,0,0,,彼らは油そそがれた者なのでしょうか？\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:33.90,0:08:36.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,わかりません\Nと答えるしかありませんね\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:38.23,0:08:39.40,Default2,,0,0,0,,わかっているのは—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:39.40,0:08:42.97,Default2,,0,0,0,,マタイ13章の小麦のような\N“王国の子たち” は—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:42.97,0:08:46.44,Default2,,0,0,0,,歴史を通じて\Nいつもいたということです\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:46.44,0:08:47.84,Default2,,0,0,0,,ですから その一部が—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:47.84,0:08:51.11,Default2,,0,0,0,,遠い地へ宣教に行ったとしても\N不思議ではありませんが—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:51.11,0:08:55.48,Default2,,0,0,0,,そうだったかどうかは\N将来はっきりするでしょう\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:55.48,0:08:58.02,Default2,,0,0,0,,わたしたちは何をすべきでしょうか？\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:58.02,0:09:04.19,Default2,,0,0,0,,もちろん 今すぐにベテルを出て\N遠い地に行こうというのではありません\N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:04.19,0:09:06.10,Default2,,0,0,0,,使徒 1章8節で イエスは—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:06.10,0:09:09.40,Default2,,0,0,0,,エルサレムにいた人々に\N話しかけていました\N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:09.40,0:09:11.53,Default2,,0,0,0,,エルサレムから見れば\Nわたしたちはすでに—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:11.53,0:09:15.00,Default2,,0,0,0,,地の最も遠い所にいることに\Nなるのかもしれません\N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:17.11,0:09:19.41,Default2,,0,0,0,,いずれにしても 大切なことは—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:19.41,0:09:23.41,Default2,,0,0,0,,移動するにしても\N自分の区域内で宣べ伝えるにしても—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:23.41,0:09:26.05,Default2,,0,0,0,,これらの忠実な者の手本に倣い—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:26.05,0:09:28.78,Default2,,0,0,0,,音信をまだ聞いていない人を\N見出すために—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:28.78,0:09:31.62,Default2,,0,0,0,,精一杯 努力することです\N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:31.62,0:09:34.01,Default2,,0,0,0,,それが遠い地であっても\N地元であってもです\N
